e.g.,
 buffer lands for a military installation that do not include management, or private lands with existing conservation easements for which landowners have not received financial compensation from public sources or regulatory assurances from the Service.);

â¢ Lands without clear title unless the existing encumbrances (
e.g.,
 liens, rights-of-way) are compatible with the objectives of the mitigation site or can be legally removed or subordinated;

â¢ Split estates (
i.e.,
 lands that have separate owners of various surface and subsurface rights, usually mineral rights), unless a remedy can be found (see below for guidance on split estates);

â¢ Private lands enrolled in government programs that compensate landowners who permanently protect, restore, or create habitat for federally listed or at-risk species (
e.g.,
 Wetland Reserve Program easements administered by the United States Department of Agriculture's Natural Resources Conservation Service);

